In article &lt;8804081905.AA05075@braden.isi.edu&gt;, braden@VENERA.ISI.EDU writes:
&gt; Craig's proposal has been roundly attacked, on the grounds that
&gt; [hiding is effectively impossible] and [it makes for maintainance
&gt; hair].  To first order, these are probably both true.

&gt; Nevertheless, I foresee that there will be a real commercial
&gt; requirement for some compartmentalization of the Internet.  If we
&gt; don't provide architected mechanisms to provide such isolation, then
&gt; companies will resort to mail bridges or just not connect.

My initial reaction is that this would be a good thing.  Then on
reflection I find that I have to ask what the difference is.  If a
machine can exchange packets with the body of the Internet, I think
everyone agrees that that host cannot be kept secret for both of the
reasons above.  But if the machine can't exchange packets with the net,
then how does it differ from a machine which isn't on the Internet at
all?  (Such a machine may have a mail connection; connections at that
level are irrelevant to this discussion.  If mail connections count,
the entire uucp world is on the Internet.)

					der Mouse

			uucp: mouse@mcgill-vision.uucp
			arpa: mouse@larry.mcrcim.mcgill.edu

